# Rebuild and Launch After App Changes

When a turn modifies ClipStack app code or project files (Swift sources, entitlements, Xcode project, etc.), finish the turn by quitting, rebuilding, and launching the app via the install script.

## When to run

Run this workflow when the turn changes anything that affects the running app binary, including:
- Swift source under `ClipStack/`
- `ClipStack.xcodeproj/` or `project.yml`
- Entitlements, Info.plist, or other app bundle config

Skip when the turn is read-only (questions, reviews, docs-only) or touches only non-app files (e.g. `README.md`).

## How to run

Run the install script from the repo root in the background so the conversation is not blocked:

```bash
./scripts/rebuild-and-run.sh
```

Use the Shell tool with `block_until_ms: 0`.

If the script is not executable: `chmod +x scripts/rebuild-and-run.sh`.

## Why this script (not raw `xcodebuild` + `open`)

Launching the app directly from `DerivedData/Build/Products/Debug/ClipStack.app` causes TCC permissions to silently break: every Xcode build produces a slightly different ad-hoc code identity at a different path, so Screen Recording / Accessibility / Clipboard grants in System Settings end up pointing at a stale identity and the running app re-prompts on every launch.

The script avoids this by:
1. Installing to a stable path (`~/Applications/ClipStack.app`).
2. Re-signing with the stable `Apple Development: Theodore Richardson (Z7APD9TUWA)` certificate.
3. Signing nested frameworks individually (no `--deep`) so framework identities stay stable.

## If permissions still appear stuck

Stale TCC rows from previous builds can survive even after re-signing. Reset them once:

```bash
./scripts/reset-permissions.sh
./scripts/rebuild-and-run.sh
```

Then re-approve the system prompts; the grants will bind to the current identity only.

## On build failure

Read `build/rebuild.log`, fix the error, then re-run the script. Do not launch a broken build.

## Brief user note

After triggering the rebuild, tell the user briefly that ClipStack is rebuilding in the background at `~/Applications/ClipStack.app` and will relaunch when done.
